The County of Ventura is evaluating proposals to renew Conditional Use Permits and expand the level
of operation at three existing sand and gravel mining operations on State Route 23 (Grimes Canyon
Road) in the County of Ventura. The three sites consist of existing sand and gravel mining projects, all
of which are proposing to expand their operations. Figure 1 shows the proposed project site locations
and local access to the sites.

manual traffic counts, analysis worksheets and other details.

There are three gravel mining sites in this study, Best Rock, Grimes Rock, and Wayne J Gravel. They
are all located along Grimes Canyon Road (SR 23) between Fillmore and Moorpark.
The Best Rock mining facility is seeking to change their existing Conditional Use Permit (CUP), which
expired in Year 2000, to extend the life of the permit and expand operations. They are looking to
combine two operations, including red rock operations and sand and gravel operations into one
operation, increase the level of output, and extend the life of their CUP to 2025. This would increase
plant production from 1 million to 2.5 million tons per year. They are also requesting the removal of a
travel restriction that prohibits trucks from using Walnut Canyon Road, and expansion of evening hours
of operation from dusk to one hour after sunset and weekend hours to include Saturday.
The Grimes Rock facility is also seeking to change their existing Conditional Use Permit (CUP) to
expand operations, increase the level of output, and extend the life of their CUP to 2025. This would
increase plant production from 0.952 million to 1.782 million tons per year. Grimes Rock is also
requesting that their existing travel restriction that prohibits travel on Walnut Canyon Road be lifted
and that Saturday mining operations are allowed under the new permit.
Also, the Wayne J facility is proposing to change their existing Conditional Use Permit (CUP) to expand
operations. They are looking to increase the level of output, and extend the life of their CUP to 2025.
This would increase plant production from 0.3 million to 1 million tons per year. Wayne J is requesting
that operating hours be extended to 24-hour operation Monday through Saturday under the new
For informational purposes, an existing fourth sand and gravel operation, Cemex, is located immediately
east of the Wayne J facility and takes access to SR 23 South of Wayne J. Although Cemex is not
currently proposing to amend their CUP, and is not a subject of this study, its contribution to truck
traffic is considered in a cumulative sense in light of the proposed projects discussed above.

the subject sites. This report titled Grimes Canyon Quarries Traffic and Circulation Study was

This section presents a brief overview of traffic analysis methodologies and concepts used in this study.
Street system operating conditions are typically described in terms of level of service. Level of service
(LOS) is a report-card scale used to indicate the quality of traffic flow on roadway segments and at
intersections. The concept and definitions were established by the Transportation Research Board of
the National Research Council and are contained in the reference document, Highway Capacity Manual,
the most recent version of which was published in 2000. Level of Service can range from Level A (free
flow, little congestion) to Level F (forced flow, extreme congestion).
Level of Service D is frequently identified as the minimum allowable Standard service level during peak
hours. The County of Ventura has identified the minimum as Level D for State highways within the
unincorporated area of the County and Level of Service C for local roadways. At signalized
intersections, most arriving traffic will clear the intersection on the first allowable green cycle under this
level of service. Mitigation measures should generally be considered when traffic conditions are
forecasted to decline to poorer levels of service.
Signalized intersections in Ventura County are analyzed based on the Intersection Capacity Utilization
(ICU) Method, a local adaptation of the Highway Capacity Manual (HCM) method of analysis that is
typically used for signalized intersections in Southern California. Level of service for intersections is
based on Table 3, which lists the level of service criteria for signalized and unsignalized intersections.
Traffic conditions for all study area unsignalized intersections were analyzed using the Highway Capacity
Manual analysis. Level of Service for unsignalized intersections is reported based upon the intersection
average, as calculated under the HCM analysis. Traffic conditions for signalized intersections were
analyzed using the ICU method. The determination of level of service calculations for intersections was
performed using the TRAFFIX software program developed by Dowling Associates.
The following peak hours were selected for analysis:
Weekday AM (peak hour between 7:00 AM and 9:00 AM)
Weekday Midday (peak hour between 9:00 AM and 11:00 AM)
Weekday PM (peak hour between 4:00 PM and 6:00 PM)
The midday peak hour was analyzed for the existing and near-term future scenarios because the sites
currently have higher traffic activity during this hour than the traditional AM and PM peak hours. This is
attributed to the nature of the operations as well as to existing CUP limitations upon hauling of
materials during the AM peak period. However, due to the low roadway volumes during this mid-day
peak hour, only the nearest intersections were analyzed during this time period. In addition, the midday
peak was only studied in the existing and near term future scenarios because, as described below,
midday traffic data is not available in the countys traffic model for 2020 or 2025.
One of the most significant issues for the study area is the level of service for SR 23, a two-lane highway
that has a low speed twisting alignment and steep grades in a portion of the study area. Two-lane rural
highways are discussed and an analysis methodology is presented in Chapters 12 and 20 of the Highway
Capacity Manual. It is important to note that the Manual acknowledges that the operation of two-lane
highways is complex, especially if there are passing lane issues and if climbing of long grades is a
significant issue. The Manual encourages simulation; however there are no widely used software
packages for simulation of two lane highways that are well suited to the project study area.
Two lane highway capacity issues are rarely analyzed in traffic impact studies that are prepared to
address projects within urbanized or urbanizing areas. As a result, the methodologies proposed for
two-lane highways are not implemented locally as frequently as other analyses, such as traffic signals.
The HCM divides two lane highways into two classes. Class I highways have an expectation of high
speed, so level of service is based in part upon prevailing speeds, as compared with desired high speeds.
Class II highways do not inspire an expectation of high speeds. They include roads that pass through
rugged terrain and other areas where motorists recognize that high speed is not possible. The most
significant two-lane highway issues in this study are thus associated with Class II highways. There is a
policy issue that is not addressed by level of service standards. This relates to SR 23, a roadway that is
clearly now a Class II facility based upon terrain and alignment, but where a Class I facility would be
The level of service criteria for Class II two-lane highways is defined in the HCM as percent time
following slower vehicles. If a vehicle is required to follow a slower vehicle, it is presumed to be
inconvenienced and not experiencing good level of service. The greater proportion of vehicles so
inconvenienced, the poorer the level of service. Table 4 indicates the relationship between level of
service and percent time following for Class II two-lane highways.
The ATE study Grimes Canyon Quarries Traffic and Circulation Study prepared for the mines in the year
2002 did not assess level of service for 2-lane roadways in the manner that is indicated in the Highway
Capacity Manual. Their study approach was based upon travel time and the ratio of traffic volume to
capacity, and not percent time following. These approaches are not consistent with the procedures in
the Highway Capacity Manual, the general authority for calculation of level of service.

page.text: Similar to other facilities, the effect of heavy vehicles can be incorporated into the analysis of two lane
highways by the use of passenger car equivalents. Heavy vehicles are converted into an equivalent
number of passenger vehicles based upon the amount of capacity they consume. The conversion factor
is based upon the length of upgrade and the steepness of the grade, and it is generally much higher than
the comparable conversion factor for multi-lane roads or for intersections. For example, the
conversion factor for a heavy vehicle on a 6% grade of 1-1.5 miles is equal to 10-11 passenger vehicles,
while at an intersection the conversion factor is 2-3 vehicles.
A software package was used for analysis of two-lane highways, Highway Capacity Analysis Program 2000
(HiCAP) developed by Catalina Engineering. The program accepts total volume, number of trucks, and
length of roadway and steepness of grade. This software package allows for analysis of basic two-lane
highways and also can evaluate mitigation measures that are normally considered to address level of
service deficiencies. The most common mitigation measures for two lane highways are provision of
additional travel lanes, climbing lanes, turnouts, or alignment improvements.
The relevant information for highway segments along SR 23 was entered, including volume, trucks,
roadway length and grade, and the results are reported. It is noted that under some situations, the
program reported results over 100%. This is realistically not possible unless the hourly volume
approaches 1700 vehicles per hour in the peak direction. The forecast was reduced to 99% and Level of
Service E in all instances where the program indicated a percentage over 100% based upon a volume of

highway facilities are developed and where complex interactions between existing traffic and new land

The traffic model provides future hourly traffic levels on study area roadways for the AM and PM peak
hours only. It does not provide forecasts of intersection turning movements, which are required to
evaluate level of service. The procedure for preparing turning movement forecasts from link volumes is
complex, however it generally provides that turning movement forecasts result in link volumes that are
consistent with the model at intersections under study. The information from these traffic forecasts is
used to assist in preparing an assessment of traffic impacts of the project in the build out Year.

For project specific impacts, the impacts of the change in traffic from the four mining operations are
evaluated against the project specific thresholds for intersections and road segments. If this change in
mining traffic does not exceed the project specific thresholds, then no individual project would exceed
the project specific thresholds. However, if the combined mining projects do exceed the project
specific threshold, then each project is assigned a percentage of the combined impact based on each
projects contribution to the combined traffic at the location the impact is occurring. This individual
project contribution is then compared to the project specific thresholds.
This process is also used for the project contributions to cumulative impacts.
The City of Moorpark has adopted Level of Service C as the peak hour operating standard for
intersection locations. Any project that increases an intersection ICU across this threshold is
considered to have a significant impact. If the Level of Service C standard is already not achieved under
the "no-project" scenarios (i.e. Scenarios 2 and 5), then a project would have a significant effect if the
with-project ICU increases by 0.02 or greater compared with the no-project ICU.

This section documents the existing conditions in the study area. The discussion presented here is
limited to specific roadways in the projects vicinity.
Streets in the site vicinity that could be affected by the expansions proposed include Grimes Canyon
Road in Ventura County, Ventura Street (SR 126) in the City of Fillmore, Broadway Road in Ventura
County, Walnut Canyon Road in Ventura County, High Street in the City of Moorpark, and Los Angeles
Avenue (SR 118) in the City of Moorpark. A description of existing conditions for these roadways,
other roadways, and their intersections appears below. Figure 2 shows the existing roadway
There are two roadways known as Grimes Canyon Road in the study area. The north branch extends
from Broadway Road to Bardsdale Avenue. This segment is designated as State Route 23. It is operated
and maintained by the State of California, Department of Transportation (Caltrans). Much of this
segment is a winding two-lane road. It has moderate grades and a rolling alignment for most of its
length, but the roadway traverses about 1.5 miles of steep grades and sharp hairpin turns as it climbs the
north escarpment of the range between Moorpark and Fillmore. There are two-foot to eight-foot
paved shoulders present along most of the length of the roadway, and it has been widened in the area of
the sharpest curves to allow heavy vehicles to travel without encroaching into opposing travel lanes.
The prevailing speeds are 40-50 mph along most of the roadway, but the steep grade section requires
most vehicles to slow to 30 mph or less. There are some sharp turns in the north end of the roadway
that also require vehicles to slow significantly.
Grimes Canyon Road provides access to all of the gravel mining extraction sites in the study area. It is
thus used at this time by trucks hauling gravel from the sites. The operation of heavy vehicles on the
steep grades of Grimes Canyon Road is thus a significant study issue.
SR 23 continues from the City of Fillmore to Bardsdale Avenue in Ventura County along a variety of
streets named A Street, Chambersburg Road, and Bellevue Road, however it is generally referred to as
Important intersections along Grimes Canyon Road include the entrances to the three mining sites, a
modified T-intersection at Bardsdale Avenue, and another modified T-intersection at Broadway Road.
The intersection of SR 23 (A Street) with SR 126 (Ventura Street) in the City of Fillmore is controlled
by a traffic signal. The other intersections are unsignalized.
The second roadway known as Grimes Canyon Road extends south from Broadway Road near SR 23 to
SR 118. This is a two-lane rural roadway maintained by the County of Ventura. It has one travel lane in
each direction on a total paved width of 20-22 feet. There are no improved shoulders for most of its
length. The alignment generally permits moderately high speeds (45 mph); however, there are several
sharper turns that require lower speeds.
The T-intersection at Grimes Canyon Road South and Broadway Road is controlled by a boulevard stop
for northbound vehicles on Grimes Canyon Road. The T-intersection at Grimes Canyon Road South
and Los Angeles Avenue (SR 118) was controlled by a boulevard stop for southbound vehicles on
Grimes Canyon Road only but since has been signalized which has since alleviated the traffic.
The County of Ventura has previously imposed conditions on gravel extraction vehicles to require them
to use Grimes Canyon Road south branch for access to SR 118. However existing traffic counts suggest
that gravel vehicles do not use the road frequently. This issue of gravel truck non-compliance is being
State Route 126 is a four-lane arterial roadway running on an east/west alignment located approximately
three miles north of the project site through the City of Fillmore. It is known as Ventura Street in the
City of Fillmore and Telegraph Road in the County area. The roadway is divided by a two way left turn
lane and is a designated truck route. The speed limit is posted at 35 mph within City Limits. Parking is
not permitted along most of the roadway. It begins in the City of Ventura and continues east through
Fillmore to I-5 and SR 14 in Santa Clarita. Land uses along SR 126 include commercial uses within the
City and vacant lots, fields and orchards outside of the City. The roadway is controlled by a traffic signal
at SR 23 near the center of Fillmore.
River Street is a two-lane local street that runs parallel to and just south of SR 126 in the City of Fillmore.
Land uses are mostly single-family residential. The intersection at A Street (SR 23) is stop-controlled.
Northbound traffic on SR 23 stopped for the signal at the SR 23/SR 126 intersection often blocks River
Street traffic, which is an important circulatory issue for the City.
Broadway Road is a two-lane rural highway running east/west along the plateau between Fillmore and
Moorpark. It begins east of Walnut Canyon Road and extends west beyond both branches of Grimes
Canyon Road. It is designated as SR 23 between the north branch of Grimes Canyon Road and Walnut
Canyon Road. It is a county highway further to the west. The State Highway segment has a good
alignment and paved shoulders permitting moderately high speeds with comfort. The county segment
has minimal paved shoulders and provides lower operating speeds.
The intersection of Broadway Road and Grimes Canyon Road north branch is controlled by an unusual
stop configuration. Eastbound and southbound are required to stop. Westbound is not required to
stop. Most of the traffic at the intersection proceeds along the SR 23 route from the north leg to the
east leg. Thus northbound SR 23 does not stop, while southbound SR 23 stops at the intersection.
The intersection of Broadway Road and Walnut Canyon Road is also an unusual configuration. The SR
23 legs are not required to stop, permitting flow between the west and south legs. The north and east
legs are required to stop. The north leg is known as Happy Camp Road. This roadway leads to the site
of a fourth gravel mining operation, CEMEX. This operation and its permit is not subject to review at
this time, however it is analyzed at activity levels comparable to the other operations in future analyses.
Waynes Way is a small collector street running on an east/west alignment. It intersects with SR 23
about one mile north of Broadway Road. It is a private roadway and serves as the main access road to
Wayne J Sand and Gravel. The roadway is controlled by a boulevard stop on Waynes Way at Grimes
Bardsdale Avenue is a two-lane roadway running on an east/west alignment located approximately two
miles north of the project site and 1.5 miles south of SR 126. Bardsdale Avenue is divided by a skip
yellow centerline. The roadway begins approximately two miles west of Grimes Canyon Road and
extends east where it turns into Bellevue Avenue at Grimes Canyon Road. The speed limit is not
posted, so a prima facie speed limit of 55 mph would apply, however prevailing speeds are lower.
Parking is not permitted along the roadway. The roadway is controlled by a stop sign at Grimes Canyon
Road. Land uses along Bardsdale Avenue are mostly agricultural.
Walnut Canyon Road is a two lane rural highway beginning at Broadway Road and extending south into
the City of Moorpark. It is designated as SR 23. The roadway is on a rolling alignment for most of its
length, permitting operating speeds of 40-45 mph and slower toward the south end of the roadway in
Moorpark. It generally provides adequate pavement width and paved shoulders. There is scattered
residential development along most of the route north of the City of Moorpark.
Within the city limits, south of Casey Road, Walnut Canyon Road becomes Moorpark Avenue. The
State Highway continues along this roadway to an intersection with State Route 118 (Los Angeles
Avenue). This intersection is signalized and has a south leg. There are several other signalized
intersections along Moorpark Avenue in Moorpark, as well as a railroad crossing. There are community
commercial (old downtown) uses along Moorpark Avenue within the City of Moorpark, including
Moorpark City Hall, a community center, senior center, library, park, and fire station.
Gravel extraction vehicles currently use Moorpark Avenue through the central business district of
Moorpark. The City of Moorpark has a goal to eliminate this activity, because it is not considered to be
compatible with the commercial activity and land use pattern in the downtown area.
Casey Road is located just north of downtown Moorpark, extending westward from the signalized
intersection at Walnut Canyon Road. Land uses along Casey Road are residential and there are
substantial development plans for the near future in the area surrounding the west end of Casey Road.
High Street is a roadway running on an east/west alignment located approximately five miles south of the
project sites in the City of Moorpark. High Street is an unmarked local roadway west of Walnut
Canyon Road. East of Walnut Canyon Road, High Street is a two-lane arterial and is marked by a double
yellow centerline. It contains bike lanes on both sides of the roadway. It extends east from Moorpark
Avenue and ends at Spring Road. The speed limit is posted at 30 mph east of Walnut Canyon Road.
The speed limit is not posted west of Walnut Canyon Road, so a prima facie speed limit of 25 mph
would apply. Parking is permitted along the roadway. Land uses along High Street are mostly
commercial uses. The roadway is controlled by a traffic signal at the intersection of Moorpark Avenue.
Poindexter Avenue is a two-lane collector roadway running on an east/west alignment located
approximately five miles south of the project site in the City of Moorpark. Poindexter Avenue contains
bike lanes on both sides of the roadway. It extends east from Gabbert Road and ends at Moorpark
Avenue (SR 23). The speed limit is not posted, so a prima facie speed limit of 25 mph would apply.
Land uses along Poindexter Avenue are mostly commercial uses to the north and residential uses to the
south. There is a middle school about a quarter mile west of the intersection with Moorpark Avenue
(SR 23). The intersection with SR 23 is signalized.
Los Angeles Avenue (State Route 118) is a 4 to 6-lane highway in the City of Moorpark, about 6 miles
south of the midpoint of the three subject gravel extraction sites. It is designated as SR 118 from
Moorpark west to Oxnard. In Moorpark, SR 118 and SR 23 both travel along Los Angeles Avenue east
to the SR 118/23 freeway located east of central Moorpark. Los Angeles Avenue continues as a
City/County street to Simi Valley. It was decommissioned as a State Highway when the SR 23 Freeway
was completed from west of Simi Valley to south of Moorpark.
West of Moorpark Avenue., SR 118 narrows to provide one lane in each direction, traveling in Ventura
County to the community of Somis and beyond. The intersection with Grimes Canyon Road South
In Somis, the intersection of SR 118 (Los Angeles Avenue) and SR 34 is a heavily congested intersection,
notoriously backing up traffic for miles in all directions during peak hours and at other times. Excessive
traffic volumes cause this condition but it is compounded by poor intersection geometrics and inefficient
traffic signal phasing caused by the existing geometrics.
Spring Road is a two-lane arterial roadway running on a north/south alignment located approximately six
miles south of the midpoint of the project sites in the City of Moorpark. The roadway has double
yellow line divider along most of its length. Spring Road extends north from Tierra Rejada Road and
ends at High Street. Parking is not permitted along the roadway. The roadway is controlled with a
traffic signal at the intersection of Los Angeles Avenue (SR 118).
State Route 23 occupies many roadways of different names in the study area. Beginning in the north, it is
known as A Street in the City of Fillmore. It is known as Chambersburg Road from the Santa Clara
River Bridge south to a sharp turn onto Bellevue Avenue. It is known as Bellevue Avenue from
Chambersburg Road west to Bardsdale Avenue. SR 23 continues south as Grimes Canyon Road over
the winding grade to Broadway Road. It travels along Broadway Road from Grimes Canyon Road to
Walnut Canyon Road. Then it travels along Walnut Canyon Road through the City of Moorpark until
the intersection with Everett Street where it becomes Moorpark Avenue and continues south to SR 118
(Los Angeles Avenue). It then travels east on Los Angeles Avenue to the 118/23 Freeway, where it
becomes a full freeway and travels south to Thousand Oaks and beyond. The State Highway Plan once
showed that SR 23 would eventually be a freeway from Moorpark to Fillmore, however that plan is
defunct. However there is interest in proving a higher quality road, probably on a new alignment,
bypassing or realigning the most problematic sections of SR 23. These sections include bypasses for
downtown Moorpark and the switchbacks north of Broadway Road on Grimes Canyon Road.

Observations of these roadways were made under existing conditions. Truck traffic was generally
lighter than the volumes assumed in the table, since the mines were not all operating at their maximum
permitted values. The observations confirmed that level of service is generally unacceptable (Level of
Service D or E) at this time on the roadway, traveling on both uphill and downhill directions, at anytime
where the directional volume exceeded 500 hourly vehicles. Under these conditions, platoons of 4-6
vehicles are regularly observed and long platoons of over 15 vehicles can be observed within 10 minutes
of observation time. In contrast, the level of service is currently acceptable (Level C or better) at
anytime when the volume is in the range of 200 vehicles per hour. Vehicles are frequently traveling
alone, and platoons of following vehicles rarely exceed 3-4 vehicles.
These observations may suggest that some of the level of service forecasts indicated by software may be
poorer than conditions that may actually materialize in forecasts. It can be stated reliably that the level
of service will move from acceptable to unacceptable conditions with a rise in hourly traffic from 200 to
500 vehicles per hour, however the precise volume that tips the roadway into the undesirable range
cannot be established precisely with analysis tools available today. It would probably be necessary to
conduct measurements of the roadway performance under a wide variety of traffic and truck volumes in
order to establish precise threshold volumes for levels of service.

of the grade, and it is the southbound traffic volume at Best Rock and Grimes Rock, which are at the
bottom of the grade. For Grimes Canyon Road south, uphill volume represents the northbound
In the northbound direction during peak periods, queues begin to form on the grade between Broadway
Road and the top of the grade near Wayne J. The queues become longer close to the top of the grade.
These queues become much longer as the traffic travels through the switchback areas down the
escarpment, reaching their maximum lengths at the most northerly hairpin turn. The queues tend to
persist from this point north due to the design speed, hard turns in the Bardsdale Avenue vicinity, and
the unequal acceleration capabilities of cars and trucks until the bridge over the Santa Clara River near
In the southbound direction during peak hours, queues begin to form around the low-speed hard turns
near Bardsdale Avenue due to the uneven acceleration capabilities and the slight grade uphill. The
observed queuing increases within the switchback area when faster platoons arrive behind slower
platoons that formed ahead of them. Queuing reaches its maximum at the top of the grade near Wayne
J. The queues persist down the grade to Broadway Road where a stop sign controls southbound traffic.
This stop sign increases the separation headway between the vehicles and reduces the amount of
queuing beyond. The downhill alignment generally limits further platoon formation.

However, per County request, under this scenario, there is no mining activity assumed (and any existing

Based on discussion with the County of Ventura staff, it has been established that traffic in the study
area has historically increased at a rate of about 2% per year. Future increases in the background traffic
volumes due to regional growth are expected to continue at this rate in the vicinity of the project.
Assuming a completion date of the year 2007, the existing traffic volumes were adjusted upward by 4%
(2% per year) to reflect area wide growth.

This section evaluates buildout traffic conditions in the study area. This forecast assumes that there will
be no sand and gravel extraction at the 3 sites or at the Cemex site, but it assumes substantial
development of urbanized land use as shown on General Plan for the County of Ventura and for the
Cities of Moorpark and Fillmore. It assumes no improvements to the circulation system. Although it is
likely that some improvements would be constructed by the year 2025, it is standard to not assume any
non-committed and funded improvements are constructed for the purpose of assessing impacts.
Scenario 4 was calculated solely from the General Plan numbers. The model reflected the 2025 year of
analysis. Mining traffic is not assumed to be in the model, so it was not removed. It is customary to not
assume a project being analyzed and any non-general plan use is not in the model, unless it can be
proven otherwise, and no mining traffic was found.
Scenario 4 was calculated using the current Ventura County Regional Traffic Model (RTM) results for
2020. Since the traffic volumes are based upon a buildout of the land use in the area, the exact year of
volumes are not important, and it is likely that the volumes for a 2020 and a 2025 year would be
approximately the same. Therefore, these numbers were assumed to be correct for the base volumes
and no additional growth rates were added to determine the year 2025 base numbers.
The County of Ventura prepared and furnished applicable forecasts using the Ventura County
Transportation Commission (VCTC) traffic model run in January 2004. This model used population and
employment distribution forecasts previously agreed upon by the County, local cities, and regional
planning and transportation agencies. These forecasts in term were developed from the General Plans
of the participating agencies. These included the calibration version, used to replicate existing traffic
conditions and verify model parameters and future forecasts for 2020 without the proposed project.
The forecasts were prepared using the most recent version of the model available at that time.

In consideration of the capabilities and limitations of the analysis tool, the AM peak hour level of service
for Grimes Canyon Road uphill south of Wayne J may be found to be Level D instead of Level E. The
PSTF is near the D/E threshold and the forecasting tool tends to over-predict congestion in this volume
range. Where the indicated volumes are above 900 vehicles per hour, the Level of Service will most
reliably be at Level E based upon observations at lower volumes today.
